# 5. Cascaded directional shadows

Large outdoor scenes need cascaded shadow maps.

A single high-resolution shadow map spread over an entire island would waste most of its resolution far from the player. Cascaded shadows divide the camera view into distance ranges.

Bevy provides `CascadeShadowConfigBuilder`; the official atmospheric-fog example explicitly tunes the first cascade distance and maximum shadow distance to match scene scale. ([Bevy][5])

```rust
use bevy::light::CascadeShadowConfigBuilder;

commands.spawn((
    DirectionalLight {
        shadows_enabled: true,
        ..default()
    },
    CascadeShadowConfigBuilder {
        first_cascade_far_bound: 20.0,
        maximum_distance: 250.0,
        ..default()
    }
    .build(),
    Transform::default(),
));
```

## Starting ranges for your terrain

For a third-person outdoor game:

```text
Cascade 1:
0–20 m
player, grass, nearby rocks

Cascade 2:
20–60 m
trees, enemies, nearby structures

Cascade 3:
60–140 m
terrain and larger vegetation

Cascade 4:
140–300 m
major terrain silhouettes
```

Exact cascade division is handled by the configuration, but these are useful conceptual targets.

## Shadow strategy by object type

| Object          | Shadow policy                                |
| --------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Player          | Always cast and receive nearby shadows       |
| NPCs            | Cast near player, disable at long LOD        |
| Major trees     | Cast within medium range                     |
| Grass           | Usually no shadow-map casting                |
| Shrubs          | Limited-range shadow casting                 |
| Terrain         | Always receive; cast where appropriate       |
| Distant terrain | No detailed shadow map                       |
| Small clutter   | Contact shadows or ambient occlusion instead |

Grass shadows are especially expensive. Use:

* Material darkening.
* SSAO.
* Contact shadows.
* Sparse grass casting only very close to the camera.

